Freeze a separate, immutable safety policy module (constraints, refusal classifiers, hard rules) outside the continually-updated weights; treat it as a non-trainable filter on inputs and outputs. For the learnable component, use constrained fine-tuning: elastic weight consolidation or L2-SP anchoring on parameters important to safety, plus LoRA adapters so base safety weights are never overwritten. Maintain a fixed "safety replay buffer" of canonical refusal, jailbreak, and constraint-violation examples, and mix it into every training batch at a guaranteed minimum ratio. Gate each new checkpoint behind a regression eval on a held-out safety suite; block promotion on any regression beyond a tight threshold. Log and version the safety eval results so forgetting is detectable and rollback is one step. Prefer KL-regularization toward the prior safe policy over unconstrained SGD. Finally, keep runtime guardrails (constitutional checks, tool-use allowlists) independent of the learned model so safety degrades gracefully even if training drifts.
